  "question": "What are your rights as a patient in Belgium?",
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "As a patient in Belgium, you have several rights that apply not only to interactions with doctors but also with dentists, pharmacists, midwives, physiotherapists, nurses, and other healthcare providers."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Your Rights\n- **Access to Information:** You have the right to clear information about your health, possible treatments, risks, and costs.\n- **Consent:** You must provide explicit consent for any examination or treatment and have the right to refuse.\n- **Privacy:** Your right to privacy includes knowing what is in your medical file and who has access to it.\n\nFor general questions about patient rights, contact the [Flemish Patient Platform](https://www.vlaamspatientenplatform.be/)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Complaints\n- **About a healthcare professional working in a hospital:** Contact the hospital's ombudsman service.\n- **About the hospital itself (infrastructure, staff behavior, rights):** Reach out to the hospital's ombudsman service. You can also contact the Department of Care.\n- **About a non-hospital healthcare provider (e.g., general practitioner, dentist, freelance nurse):** Contact the [Federal Ombudsman for Patient Rights](https://www.health.belgium.be/)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Ombudsman services aim to resolve questions and complaints efficiently, saving you from a lengthy and costly legal process. However, you retain the right to file a complaint in court."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Medical Errors or Accidents\nIf you or a loved one is a victim of a medical error or accident, you can contact the [Medical Accident Fund (FMO)](https://www.health.belgium.be/). The fund investigates responsibility and provides compensation if conditions are met, such as:\n- Permanent disability of 25% or more.\n- Inability to work for 6 consecutive or non-consecutive months within a year.\n- Significant deterioration in quality of life.\n- Death of the victim."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Claims are accepted for incidents occurring after April 2, 2010. For earlier cases, you must pursue legal action. Additionally, you can always seek a friendly resolution or go to court."
