  "content": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The subsistence income (leefloon) is a minimum income provided to individuals who lack sufficient means of subsistence. It is part of the right to social integration and is managed by the Public Social Welfare Center (OCMW)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Eligibility Criteria\nTo qualify for the leefloon, you must meet all the following conditions:\n- **Residency:** You must reside and have your main address in Belgium.\n- **Age:** You must be at least 18 years old, except if:\n  - You are married.\n  - You have a dependent child.\n  - You are pregnant.\n- **Legal Status:**\n  - You are Belgian or a family member of an EU citizen.\n  - Recognized as a political refugee, stateless, or a foreigner registered in the population register.\n- **Insufficient Means:** Your household income is below the subsistence threshold, and you cannot acquire sufficient income.\n- **Willingness to Work:** You must be willing to work unless medically or reasonably exempt (e.g., still studying or addressing other issues first).\n- **Claim Other Benefits:** You must apply for any other benefits you may be entitled to (e.g., unemployment benefits or disability allowances)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Application Procedure\n1. **Contact the OCMW:** Visit the OCMW in the municipality where you reside. If you are a student, apply where you are registered in the population register.\n2. **Initial Meeting:** Meet with a social worker to discuss your situation.\n3. **Social Investigation:** The social worker will conduct an investigation to determine your eligibility. Your cooperation is required.\n4. **Decision:** The OCMW will decide if you are eligible for the leefloon or suggest alternative support.\n5. **Integration Plan:** If approved, a ‘Geïndividualiseerd Project voor Maatschappelijke Integratie’ (GPMI) will be agreed upon within three months to support your social integration."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Required Documents\nBring the following to your first meeting:\n- Identity card.\n- Proof of current income (if any) for yourself and other household members (excluding minor children).\n- Overview of your savings.\n\nAdditional documents may be requested by the social worker."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Amount\nThe monthly leefloon amount depends on your living situation:\n1. **Cohabiting:** Sharing a household with another adult, regardless of the relationship.\n2. **Single:** Living alone.\n3. **Cohabiting with Dependent Child(ren):** Living with a minor child you support. If you have a partner, this amount applies to both of you, provided they meet the same conditions."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The leefloon is reduced by any income you or your household receives. The OCMW may also consider income from your parents or adult children living with you. Notify the OCMW immediately about changes in your family or financial situation."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Repayment\nIn most cases, the leefloon does not need to be repaid. However, the social worker can provide more specific information regarding your situation."
    },
    {
      "type": "source",
      "url": "https://www.mi-is.be/"
    }
  ]
