  "question": "What is a negative advance directive, and how can it be set up in Belgium?",
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "A negative advance directive allows patients to refuse specific medical procedures or treatments in cases where they can no longer express their wishes (e.g., due to dementia or coma). This includes refusing resuscitation, artificial ventilation, radiation therapy, etc."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Procedure\n1. **Draft the Directive:** Write down your refusals clearly. You can use a model document available on the [LEIF website](https://www.leif.be/). Printed versions and LEIF cards listing your advance directives can also be requested.\n2. **Optional Presence of a Physician:** It is recommended to draft the directive in the presence of a doctor to confirm your competence and avoid disputes.\n3. **Designate a Representative:** Optionally, appoint someone to advocate for your rights if you become unable to do so.\n4. **Distribute Copies:** Keep the original directive, provide copies to your trusted representative, and share one with your treating physician to include in your medical file."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Legal Validity\n- The negative advance directive is legally binding, and physicians are required to respect it.\n- It remains valid indefinitely unless you revoke it."
    },
    {
      "type": "source",
      "url": "https://www.leif.be/"
    }
