  "question": "How does organ donation after death work in Belgium?",
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Organ donation after death can save lives for patients with chronic and irreversible conditions. If you pass away due to brain or heart failure, your organs, tissues, and cells can be used for transplantation. In Belgium, you are automatically considered a potential donor unless you explicitly refuse during your lifetime."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Conditions\n1. **Automatic Consent:**\n   - If you are registered in the population register (or have been in the foreigner’s register for at least six months), you are automatically considered a potential donor unless you opt out.\n2. **Explicit Registration:**\n   - To ensure your wishes are respected, you can formally register a 'Declaration of Consent for Human Body Material Donation.'\n3. **Minors and Incapacitated Individuals:**\n   - Competent minors aged 12 and above can register their wishes.\n   - For incompetent minors, parents or guardians can only express opposition to donation.\n   - For incompetent adults, their legal representative, guardian, or closest relative can express opposition."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Procedure\nThe declaration allows you to explicitly consent to, oppose, or withdraw a previous decision for the following:\n- Organ donation for transplantation.\n- Tissue and cell donation for transplantation.\n- Donation of organs, tissues, and cells for the production of medicines.\n- Donation of organs, tissues, and cells for scientific research.\n\n(Note: This is different from donating your body to science.)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "You can register your wishes:\n1. At your **general practitioner’s** office.\n2. At your **municipal office**.\n3. Through **online self-registration** on [mijngezondheid.be](https://www.mijngezondheid.be/).\n\n**Important:** Online self-registration is not available for minors or individuals who cannot express their will."
